00:41:22.320 --> 00:41:28.560
though, a little bit to start and talk about what Connect is, if you haven't heard of Connect.

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:33.840
It's our platform for publishing all of the things that you build in R and Python,

00:41:33.840 --> 00:41:40.800
your data products, to a server that can be used to execute your content and share it with

00:41:40.800 --> 00:41:46.479
other people inside of your organization. So you can create things like Shiny apps,

00:41:46.479 --> 00:41:53.040
interactive Python applications, APIs, documents. You can run those things on a schedule.

00:41:53.040 --> 00:41:58.959
You can share them with people. And Connect helps you do all of those things in a way that you can

00:41:58.959 --> 00:42:05.120
manage as a data scientist without having to worry about standing up the necessary infrastructure

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:09.439
yourself once you get over the hurdle of putting Connect online itself.

00:42:11.360 --> 00:42:19.439
But today, if you are using RStudio Connect, fundamentally, even though you can run

00:42:20.399 --> 00:42:25.840
multiple versions of R and multiple versions of Python for your different content, you can have

00:42:25.840 --> 00:42:32.399
multiple package sets that support your different content items. Those content items are sandboxed

00:42:32.399 --> 00:42:39.919
apart from one another so that my Shiny application doesn't mess with Joe's Python app.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:49.600
All of those things, fundamentally, are running using local processes on the same host or container

00:42:49.600 --> 00:42:56.239
as the Connect server itself. And that's what we're calling attention to on this slide because

00:42:56.879 --> 00:43:05.840
it highlights our next iteration of what comes next for Connect. So what we've enabled now with

00:43:05.840 --> 00:43:14.479
the RStudio launcher product and packaging that inside of Connect itself is a method of

00:43:14.479 --> 00:43:21.919
off-host content execution specifically in Kubernetes environments. So using this paradigm,

00:43:22.639 --> 00:43:28.879
Kubernetes is used to execute content and jobs are running external to the container

00:43:28.879 --> 00:43:34.399
that's running Connect itself. So we've added this layer of separation.

00:43:35.040 --> 00:43:43.760
Why you might want to do that is to make use of native execution paradigms. You might want that

00:43:43.760 --> 00:43:49.600
additional layer of separation between your content items. You might want to run different

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:56.320
underlying container images or operating systems, even, to support different content items. It could

00:43:56.320 --> 00:44:00.800
make migrating from operating system to operating system easier in the future.

00:44:00.800 --> 00:44:07.600
A lot of great benefits come from adopting this kind of execution paradigm. So it can be very

00:44:07.600 --> 00:44:15.040
powerful both from a user perspective as a data scientist and also from an admin perspective. If

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:25.600
you or your organization has decided to adopt Kubernetes, we now support that type of environment

00:44:25.600 --> 00:44:35.520
execution in a much more native way. So if you are of the admin perspective, these are kind of

00:44:35.520 --> 00:44:45.280
the nitty-gritty. The Connect requirements for running in-off-host execution are a modern version

00:44:45.280 --> 00:44:51.280
of Connect itself. It should be running, hopefully, like the latest version of Connect, which our

00:44:51.280 --> 00:44:58.159
latest release is our September edition. But at the very least, use our July edition, which is when we

00:44:58.159 --> 00:45:05.679
announced the public data. You need a valid license, a TLS certificate, and you need to use a

00:45:05.679 --> 00:45:13.679
Postgres database, and you need some sort of file storage, either NFS or EFS, to set this up.

00:45:14.639 --> 00:45:23.280
